{{Quote|I can't shake him!|Luke Skywalker, flying against DS-61-4|<ref name="anh" />}}
'''DS-61-4''', nicknamed "'''Dark Curse'''," served the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]] as a [[Starfighter/Legends|starfighter]] [[Pilot/Legends|pilot]] during the [[Time/Legends|time]] before, and during, the [[Battle of Yavin/Legends|Battle of Yavin]]. An eventual member of [[Black Squadron (Galactic Empire)/Legends|Black Squadron]], he participated in various Imperial campaigns before being [[Death/Legends|killed]] by [[Rebel pilot/Legends|Rebel pilot]] [[Wedge Antilles/Legends|Wedge Antilles]] during the [[Battle of Yavin/Legends|Battle of Yavin]], where the [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Rebel Alliance]] attacked the [[DS-1 Orbital Battle Station/Legends|first Death Star]] [[Battle station/Legends|battle station]] that DS-61-4 and others in his [[Squadron/Legends|squadron]] tried to defend.

==Biography==
[[File:Dark_Curse_XWM.png|thumb|left|250px|"Dark Curse" piloting his TIE fighter]]
DS-61-4 was a [[TIE pilot]] in the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire's]] [[Imperial Navy/Legends|navy]] during the [[Galactic Civil War/Legends|Galactic Civil War]] fought between the Empire and the [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Rebel Alliance]]. At some point, he was given the nickname "Dark Curse," and had survived numerous assaults against dissenter worlds, such as the [[Planet/Legends|planets]] [[Ralltiir/Legends|Ralltiir]] and [[Dac/Legends|Mon Calamari]].<ref name="DS614card" /> Sometime prior to the Imperial attack on the [[Moon/Legends|moon]] [[Yavin 4/Legends|Yavin 4]] in [[0 BBY/Legends|0 BBY]],<ref name="NEC" /> DS-61-4 was assigned to the Empire's [[DS-1 Orbital Battle Station/Legends|first Death Star]] [[Battle station/Legends|battle station]] as a member of<ref name="anh" /> [[Dark Lord of the Sith/Legends|Dark Lord of the Sith]] [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Darth Vader's]] elite [[TIE/ln space superiority starfighter/Legends|TIE Fighter]] unit,<ref name="Black Squadron CSWE">{{CSWECite|I|77|Black Squadron}}</ref> [[Black Squadron (Galactic Empire)/Legends|Black Squadron]].<ref name="B4card">{{CCG|set=A New Hope Limited|cardname=Black 4}}</ref> While serving on the Death Star, DS-61-4 had planned on retiring from military service, with the conclusion of his next combat mission.<ref name="DS614card" />

Flying the TIE Fighter [[Black 4]],<ref name="B4card" /> DS-61-4 flew with his fellow Black Squadron [[Pilot/Legends|pilots]] against the Rebel assault on the [[Death Star/Legends|Death Star]] during the [[Battle of Yavin/Legends|Battle of Yavin]]. During the initial confusion of the battle, DS-61-4 had managed to maneuver his TIE Fighter behind the [[T-65 X-wing starfighter/Legends|X-wing]] [[Red Five/Legends|Red Five]], flown by the [[Noob|rookie]] [[Rebel pilot/Legends|Rebel pilot]] [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]], and was able to score a direct hit on the enemy [[Starfighter/Legends|starfighter]]. DS-61-4's damage to the X-wing caused Skywalker to call for assistance from his fellow [[Red Squadron (Rebel Alliance)/Legends|Red Squadron]] pilots. Discovering that he was unable to outmaneuver the pursuing DS-61-4, Skywalker received help from a fellow Rebel pilot, [[Wedge Antilles/Legends|Wedge Antilles]], who was able to destroy DS-61-4's TIE Fighter in a [[Corellian Slip]] maneuver, ensuring Skywalker's survival.<ref name="anh" />

==Equipment==
DS-61-4 wore the standard [[Imperial military uniforms/Legends|uniform]] for [[TIE pilot]]s.<ref name="anh" />

==Behind the scenes==
[[File:TurrPhennir.png|thumb|right|220px|Turr Phennir, whose older brother, Cartha, was considered to be the same character as DS-61-4, although that was never canonized]]
DS-61-4's first appearance was in the [[1976]] [[Star Wars: A New Hope (novelization)|novelization]] of the [[original trilogy]] film [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'': Episode IV ''A New Hope'']],<ref name="EP4NOVEL">[[Star Wars: A New Hope (novelization)|''Star Wars Episode IV: A New Hope'' novelization]]</ref> before appearing in the [[1977]] film itself, in which he flew against Luke Skywalker during the Rebel attack on the Death Star.<ref name="anh" /> His scenes were shot on Stage 8 at [[Elstree Studios]] between [[June 17]] and [[June 28]], [[1976]].<ref name="MakingOf">''[[The Making of Star Wars: The Definitive Story Behind the Original Film]]''</ref> He was first identified as DS-61-4, with the nickname of "Dark Curse," by the [[1996]] ''[[A New Hope Limited]]'' expansion set of the [[Star Wars Customizable Card Game|''Star Wars'' Customizable Card Game]].<ref name="DS614card" /> Of note, in [[1998]], the card game would create a card for another character, [[Dodson Makraven/Legends|Dodson Makraven]], in the ''[[Special Edition Limited]]'' expansion set,<ref name="makraven">{{CCG|set=Special Edition Limited|cardname=OS-72-2 In Obsidian 2}}</ref> using an image of DS-61-4.<ref name="DS614card" />

According to the ''Star Wars'' Customizable Card Game's [[2000]] ''[[Death Star II Limited]]'' card entitled "[[Major/Legends|Major]] [[Turr Phennir]]," Phennir had an older brother who was [[Death/Legends|killed]] by Wedge Antilles during the Battle of [[Yavin Prime/Legends|Yavin]].<ref name="Card-CCG-Major Turr Phennir">{{CCG|set=Death Star II Limited|cardname=Major Turr Phennir}}</ref> Phennir's older brother was later on named as [[Cartha|"Chaser" Cartha]] in the [[2014]] [[StarWars.com]] article [[Star Wars: The Essential Guide to Warfare Author's Cut|''Star Wars: The Essential Guide to Warfare'' Author's Cut]] which featured cut content from [[2012]]'s ''[[The Essential Guide to Warfare]]''.<ref name="AC10">{{SW|url=news/star-wars-the-essential-guide-to-warfare-authors-cut-part-10-the-rise-of-the-empire|series=Star Wars: The Essential Guide to Warfare Author's Cut|text=Part 10: The Rise of the Empire}}</ref> Notably [[Paul R. Urquhart]], an author for ''The Essential Guide to Warfare'', stated his original intent to make Cartha and DS-61-4 the same character, although that material did not make it into the final book or the Author's Cut article.<ref name="Urquhart">{{JCFCite|url=posts/51719258|board=Literature|thread=The Official StarWars.com Blog Thread - That's right, I went there|user=[[Paul R. Urquhart|Thrawn McEwok]]|date=2014-07-30|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151002203019/http://boards.theforce.net/threads/the-official-starwars-com-blog-thread-thats-right-i-went-there.50015309/page-46}}</ref>

===Inconsistencies===
[[File:DS-55-2.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Images of what the ''Star Wars'' Customizable Card Game identified as DS-61-4 in Black 4 were identified as several different designations in the ''Star Wars Trading Card Game'', with this image being used to represent TIE Fighter DS-55-2.]]
In the [[1998]] ''[[Star Wars Encyclopedia]]'', it is erroneously stated that DS-61-4 "''[&hellip;]was an Imperial TIE pilot who survived the Battle of Yavin.''"<ref name="swe">''[[Star Wars Encyclopedia]]''</ref> This was later on repeated in [[2008]]'s ''[[The Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia]]''.<ref name="CSWE">{{CSWECite|I|212|DS-61-4}}</ref> However, his death was clearly portrayed in ''A New Hope'' when Wedge Antilles destroyed his TIE Fighter, after it had scored a hit on Red Five.<ref name="anh" />

Further, the [[2002]] [[A New Hope (TCG)|''A New Hope'']] expansion of the ''[[Star Wars Trading Card Game]]'' used a film still of Black 4 to represent TIE Fighter [[DS-3-12]],<ref name="TCG">{{TCG|set=A New Hope|cardname=TIE Fighter DS-3-12|link=https://swtcg.com/Content/Images/Cards/ANH/TIE_Fighter_DS_3_12.webp?v=2}}</ref> while TIE Fighters [[DS-55-2]]<ref name="TCG2">{{TCG|set=Battle of Yavin|cardname=TIE Fighter DS-55-2|link=https://swtcg.com/Content/Images/Cards/BOY/TIE_Fighter_DS_55_2.webp?v=2}}</ref> and [[DS-73-5]] were depicted with film stills of Black 4 in the [[2003]] [[Battle of Yavin (TCG)|''Battle of Yavin'']] set.<ref name="TCG3">{{TCG|set=Battle of Yavin|cardname=TIE Fighter DS-73-5|link=https://swtcg.com/Content/Images/Cards/BOY/TIE_Fighter_DS_73_5.webp?v=2}}</ref> This article, as well as other articles linked to DS-61-4, treat DS-61-4 in Black 4 as the true identities of the TIE pilot and fighter from the ''A New Hope'' film, and treat the other designations as [[canon]] subjects separate from DS-61-4 and Black 4.

